title.$t: MCDHH Deaf Empowerment Symposium: Elijah Buchholz

media$title.$t: MCDHH Deaf Empowerment Symposium: Elijah Buchholz

media$description.$t:
Missouri Commission for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing presented their annual Deaf Empowerment Symposium 2012:

"Changes with Missouri Department of Mental Health" by Elijah Buchholz

About Elijah Buchholz: He has been a mental health counselor for the past 8 years, working with both mentally ill and substance addicted clients, hearing and deaf, impatient and outpatient.  Elijah has conducted numerous trainings for both mental health clinicians and interpreters across Kansas and Missouri.  In addition, Elijah was born to a deaf family and has been interpreting informally most of his life and formally for the past 11 years.

title.$t: MCDHH Deaf Empowerment Symposium: Hollie Spink

media$title.$t: MCDHH Deaf Empowerment Symposium: Hollie Spink

media$description.$t:
Missouri Commission for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing presented their annual Deaf Empowerment Symposium 2012:

"Onward & Upward: Navigating the Unique Obstacles within the Mental Health Field as a Deaf Professional" by Hollie Barnes Spink

About Hollie Barnes Spink: She is a statewide school psychology consultant for the Wisconsin Department of Public Instruction.  She grew up mainstreamed in a deaf/hard of hearing program and was raised using total communication.  Ms. Barnes Spink obtained a Bachelor's degree in Psychology, with an emphasis in Neuropsychology.  She went on to finish her graduate training in Education and Counseling Psychology from University of Missouri.  As a member of the Wisconsin Educational Services Program Deaf and Hard of Hearing Outreach Team, Ms. Barnes Spink provide consultation in mental health, counseling, psychoeducational evaluations, suicide prevention, behavior modification, and many other areas. Lastly she is also a member of the Wisconsin Mental Health Steering Committee, which focuses upon the process of implementing statewide Mental Health services for the deaf and hard of hearing community in Wisconsin.

title.$t: Pink Wings of Hope: Courage

media$title.$t: Pink Wings of Hope: Courage

media$description.$t:
While October is recognized as National Breast Cancer Awareness Month, DEAF Inc. Breast Cancer Support Group, now named "Pink Wings of Hope", will be releasing a series of videos this month to promote the support group. 

Five brave deaf women shares there story about discovering breast cancer and their frustration in communication access while seeking support. These stories lead to the formation of DEAF Inc.'c Pink Wings of Hope, a deaf and hard of hearing breast cancer support group in St. Louis. This is a fifth video out of a series of five videos.

title.$t: DEAF Inc.'s Emergency Kit Preparedness Video

media$title.$t: DEAF Inc.'s Emergency Kit Preparedness Video

media$description.$t:
DEAF Inc. presents one of their emergency disaster preparedness videos:
Emergency Kit Preparedness

With many disaster preparedness materials online being inaccessible to the population whose primary language is American Sign Language, DEAF Inc. is pleased to announce the completion of the Emergency Kit preparedness video in sign language. It's important that for those who are deaf or hard of hearing prepare themselves and their family for disasters as they will have an emergency kit to survive after a disaster.

title.$t: DEAF Inc. eNews: Deafilicious Wrap Up and Upcoming Workshops/Events!

media$title.$t: DEAF Inc. eNews: Deafilicious Wrap Up and Upcoming Workshops/Events!

media$description.$t:
The 2nd annual Deafilicious Fashion Benefit has exceeded our expectations! On June 10th, at G.S.L.A.D., many beautiful ladies and handsome men walked on the cat walk and showed off fabulous clothes from Maurice's, Back On Rack, Old Navy, Kohl's and other different clothing stores. The audience enjoyed the show while they ate delicious meal served by San-Sai Japanese Grill.

We raised three times more funds than last year! The funds will go to programs for deaf and hard of hearing people at DEAF Inc. DEAF Inc. wants to thank all of the sponsors, exhibitors, volunteers and attendees who made this fabulous event a huge success!

You can check out pictures from the Deafilicious Fashion Benefit, by visiting DEAF Inc. Facebook page. We hope to  see you all at the next Deafilicious! Go to our Faceboo: http://facebook.com/deafinc

Also, we have more information on our upcoming workshops and events! Please watch our eNews video.

content.$t:
The 2nd annual Deafilicious Fashion Benefit has exceeded our expectations! On June 10th, at G.S.L.A.D., many beautiful ladies and handsome men walked on the cat walk and showed off fabulous clothes from Maurice's, Back On Rack, Old Navy, Kohl's and other different clothing stores. The audience enjoyed the show while they ate delicious meal served by San-Sai Japanese Grill.

We raised three times more funds than last year! The funds will go to programs for deaf and hard of hearing people at DEAF Inc. DEAF Inc. wants to thank all of the sponsors, exhibitors, volunteers and attendees who made this fabulous event a huge success!

You can check out pictures from the Deafilicious Fashion Benefit, by visiting DEAF Inc. Facebook page. We hope to  see you all at the next Deafilicious! Go to our Faceboo: http://facebook.com/deafinc

Also, we have more information on our upcoming workshops and events! Please watch our eNews video.

title.$t: DEAF Inc. Special Announcement: The battle is not over for SB188!

media$title.$t: DEAF Inc. Special Announcement: The battle is not over for SB188!

media$description.$t:
The battle is not over for SB188!

Governor Nixon have vetoed Senate Bill (SB) 188 at Old Courthouse in Downtown St. Louis. As of now, SB188 is going back to the Missouri Senate. The Senate has to decide if they want to override Governor Nixon's veto.  You can learn more by watch the signing video or read below.

What is SB 188?

It is a bill that changes that law related to Missouri Human Rights Act and employment discrimination. There are many businesses in Missouri that wants SB 188 to pass. Most of these businesses are not from Missouri. If SB 188 passes, it will make it easier for businesses to get dismissed from discriminating deaf and hard of hearing people.

What's happening with SB 188 right now?

Before Governor Nixon vetoed SB 188, the vote in the Senate was 25 in favor and 9 against. If these Senators continue to vote the same, it will pass and override the Governor's veto in the Senate. An override of a veto requires a 2/3rd votes or 67% of the votes by both the Senate and the House. If it passes the Senate, it still needs to go and be approved by the House, but let's try to prevent this from entering the House by defeating SB 188 in the Senate.

Okay, how do I prevent SB188 from passing in the Senate?

We need to call and convince 3 or more legislators to change their mind and vote against SB 188. We need to get a total of 12 or more Senators to vote against SB 188.  So far, we only 9 Senators voting against SB 188.

We need your help again! We need you to call your local Senator and others to convince them to change their vote. The Senate may vote on this bill anytime within 2 weeks, so call today!

If you don't know who is your local legislator, go to  http://www.senate.mo.gov and type your zip code (with 9 digits).  You will find who is your local legislator in your district.  It is really easy to call his office and say just a few words. Your call and voice do matter!

We hope that this article (or video) helped you fight for your human rights as a deaf and hard of hearing individual. If you have any questions, please contact us at 314-714-6400 or email us at info@deafinc.org.

Call your local Senator today and say
"Vote Nay to SB 188!"

title.$t: DEAF Inc.'s Earthquake Preparedness Video

media$title.$t: DEAF Inc.'s Earthquake Preparedness Video

media$description.$t:
DEAF Inc. presents one of their emergency disaster preparedness videos:
Earthquake Preparedness 

First of all, many people think earthquake only happen in California.  Not true.  Missouri has a large fault called New Madrid Fault, which is about 2.5 hours drive south of St. Louis.  Researchers and scientists have predicted that there will be a big earthquake in St. Louis in the near future. So, it's important to us that we be prepared now.

To increase awareness about earthquakes and help deaf and hard of hearing people become better prepared for disasters, DEAF Inc. created a Earthquake Preparedness video in sign language for our community. This video has three parts:

    * How can you be prepared for earthquake?,
    * What do do during an earthquake?
    * What to do after an earthquake?

Watch the video to be prepared!

title.$t: Funny Stories from 4 Deaf Breast Cancer Survivors

media$title.$t: Funny Stories from 4 Deaf Breast Cancer Survivors

media$description.$t:
Four brave deaf women shares their stories about going through their chemotherapy/treatments as they used humor to survive through it. One of the best medicine for going through breast cancer or any cancer treatments is the laughter. This is a third video out of a series of three videos.

"Against the assault of the laughter, nothing can stand." - Mark Twain. 

For more information, go to: http://www.deafinc.org/pink
